Cum fuerint imbres autumnales 30 tonitrua crebra tunc nasci et maxime e tonitrubus: tenerrima autem verno esse '' (H. N. xix. 3). From this notion about the thunder it was called ‘tuber ceraunium.' The ‘tuberes’ mentioned by Martial (xiii. 42, 43), and re- ferred to by Ruperti, were a sort of apple, as Pliny shows (xv.14): and, as Martial says they grew upon trees, Ruperti need not have been deceived. Pliny (xix. 2) says the best ‘tubera’ came from Africa. The epicure Allidius (which name is variously written Alledius, Aledius, Atidius) wishes all Libya, the greatest granary of Rome, would turn her corn-fields into truffle grounds. He is introduced in aparenthesis.
